#open-question(title: [Can NET/DNase Imbalance Stratify ME/CFS Patients for Thrombo-Inflammatory Phenotype?])[
Would ME/CFS patients with elevated NET/DNase ratios form a distinct clinical subgroup (thrombo-inflammatory ME/CFS) characterised by more severe orthostatic intolerance, higher D-dimer, microclot presence, and potentially differential response to NET-targeting therapies such as DNase I? The Garcia et al. @GarciaLabroucheColomer2024 finding that H3cit and H3cit-DNA levels predicted hospitalisation among ambulatory patients suggests the ratio has prognostic as well as diagnostic value. A validation study would measure NET markers, DNase activity, calprotectin, D-dimer, and microclot presence in n >= 100 ME/CFS patients versus healthy and long COVID controls, with clinical correlation to orthostatic intolerance severity and PEM duration.
] <oq:net-dnase-stratification>
